ed states/ohio/adams/west union/"], "contributor": ["ohio history connection, columbus, oh"], "date": "1937-12-02", "dates": ["1937-12-02"], "description": ["BUSINESS OUTLOOK STATE AND NATION _ Average Ohio Farmer Has Better Position Than Producers Elsewhere In adapting government business outiook reports to Ohio farm condi tions members of the Ohio State Uni versity rurai economics department say The average Ohio farmer is in a better economic position than the average United States farmer for the next 12 months The Ohio farmer has a relatively large supply of live stock and also has a fairly large feed supply The 1934 and 1936 drouths forced considerable liquidation of livestock in the drouth areas and from January 1 1934 to January 1 1937 the number of cattle and calves in the United States declined 11 per cent but there was a decrease of only two peT cent in the numbers of cattle and calves in Ohio Farmers in the whole nation reduced the numbers of milk cows by seven per cent but the num bers decreased only two per cent in Ohio and the number of hogs on farms in Ohio declined only 116 per cent while the decline was 27 per cent for the country as a whole The presence of the fairly large numbers of livestock in Ohio and the prospects"], "digitized": true, "extract_timestamp": "2025-07-02T21:22:19.687Z", "group": ["ndnp/ohi", "ohio-historical-society-awardee"], "hassegments": false, "id": "http://www.loc.gov/resource/sn83035189/1937-12-02/ed-1/?sp=10", "image_url": ["https://tile.loc.gov/image-services/iiif/service:ndnp:ohi:batch_ohi_fleur_ver01:data:sn83035189:00516993777:1937120201:0667/full/pct:6.25/0/default.jpg#h=455&w=340", "https://tile.loc.gov/image-services/iiif/service:ndnp:ohi:batch_ohi_fleur_ver01:data:sn83035189:00516993777:1937120201:0667/full/pct:12.5/0/default.jpg#h=910&w=680", "https://tile.loc.gov/text-services/word-coordinates-service?segment=/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_fleur_ver01/data/sn83035189/00516993777/1937120201/0667.xml&format=alto_xml"]